egration of Public Health Care -- t13 Nail Salons, Toxics, and Health: Organizing for a Better Work Environment -- t14 Conclusion – Health Matters: Research in Practice -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Health Matters, contributors from a range of disciplinary and interdisciplinary traditions address multiple dimensions of health care, such as nursing, midwifery, home care, pharmaceuticals, medical education, and palliative care. Through their explorations, the book poses questions about the role that the forms of expertise associated with evidence-based health care play in shaping how we understand and organize health services. Authors critique instrumental, managerial ways of knowing health care and focus on how such ways of knowing limit our understandings of and responses to health care problems and are linked with the growing commodification, individualization, and privatization of Canadian health services. Working with analytic perspectives such as feminism, Marxist political economy, critical ethnography, science and technology studies, governmentality studies, and institutional ethnography, the volume demonstrates how critical social science perspectives contribute alternative perspectives about what counts as health care problems and how to best to address them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEvidence-based medicinezCanada. 0aMedical carexResearchzCanada. 0aMedical carezCanadaxEvaluation. 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aSocial medicinezCanada. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  acritical social science.  aevidence-based decision making.  ahealth care.  ahealth services research.  ahome care.  amedicine.  aneo-liberalism.  apublic health.  asocial work.1 aArmstrong, Hugh , eeditor.4edt